<p>NetFlix has their hands in other honey-pots as well, though they seem to be in the process of extricating themselves from some of these side-ventures.  One such venture is Red Envelope Entertainment, the documentary investment arm of NetFlix responsible for such blockbusters as <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0492487/">Small Town Gay Bar</a>, <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0762117/">Maxed Out: Hard Times, Easy Credit and the Era of Predatory Lenders</a>, and <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0386757/">Running with Arnold.</a></p>
<p>While those were the most absurd titles I could find in the 100 film line-up of Red Envelope, the documentary investment arm of the company did surprisingly well, with <a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&amp;sid=aCynTzP.WKpY" target="_blank">Piper Jaffrey analysts estimating gross revenues</a> around $10-30 million.</p>
<p><span id="more-30227"></span><br />
Chris Albrecht <a href="http://newteevee.com/2008/07/23/netflix-rightly-ditches-film-funding/" target="_blank">says today over at NewTeeVee</a> that NetFlix was right to ditch their attempt at running a studio.  From a business perspective, this may or may not be true, but for the reasons he gives it just doesn&#8217;t scan for me:</p>
<blockquote><p>Netflix doesn’t need to be in the business of finding little films that could. Yes, it was great that it funded documentaries, but the movie rental company has much bigger fish to fry, and companies such as <a href="http://newteevee.com/2008/07/21/snagfilms-best-thing-for-docs-since-netflix/" target="_blank">Snagfilms</a> are stepping up to distribute documentaries.</p>
<p>Netflix’s biggest priority has to be getting more content for its online streaming services. <a href="http://newteevee.com/2008/07/14/roku-netflixbox-and-the-future-of-tv/#comment-241171" target="_blank">Stacey’s predictions</a> about the dearth of “Watch Instantly” content have come true, and after two weeks with the Netflix-streaming Roku box, I’m left to choose between watching old episodes of <em>Buck Rogers</em> or <em>100 Sailing Mistakes</em>.</p>
<p>Once it has that problem licked, Netflix can then focus on its content delivery and start <a href="http://newteevee.com/2008/07/18/i-want-my-i-want-my-hd-stream/" target="_blank">streaming in HD</a>.</p></blockquote>
<p><img align="right" class="alignright size-full wp-image-29118" title="netflix_roku_streaming" src="http://mashable.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/07/netflix_roku_streaming.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" />Aside from the glaringly obvious fact that &#8220;Watch Instantly&#8221; is far from dead, isn&#8217;t finding and creating unique content working to solve the problem of not having enough unique and interesting content on the service?</p>
<p>Sure, I&#8217;d love to have the online videos in HD.  Absolutely I&#8217;d love to have more mainstream movies and TV on the on-demand service quicker. Ending unique production investment seems counter to Chris&#8217;s arguments.</p>
<p>If I had my druthers, I&#8217;d encourage NetFlix to invest in and forge relationships even <em>more</em> with alternative content providers.  The seeds have been sewn to take their on-demand services and throw them to the livingroom.  Garner more compelling and unique content by striking deals with episodic content producers. It&#8217;ll create incentive for Internet video producers to keep producing, and it&#8217;ll turn the uber-simple Roku device into the new cable-box.</p>
